summary: Nah you're just justifying it because you like the show, lol. Killing Eve is literally the worst representation we can get and...
question: Nah you're just justifying it because you like the show, lol. Killing Eve is literally the worst representation we can get and is a step back for lesbians tbh. Straight men being bad have nothing to prove. My homophobic mother /loves/ this show. It's media that's safe for straight people to consume because the lesbian is the bad person.
answer: i vehemently disagree. killing eve is the kind of show that is ahead of its time. villanelle is a bad person, and so what? yeah, she’s cruel, ruthless, morally depraved, but she’s also endearing and vulnerable and the genuine connection she has with eve is fascinating. a complex romantic relationship between two women that completely exists outside of male influence is awesome. her being a “bad person” (an oversimplified label anyway) is part of the concept of the show. the queer fanbase is much more prominent than than the straight one anyway and frankly idgaf that a homophobe watches it when this show means so much to me and other wlw. queer characters don’t have to be virtuous in order to get represented.

summary: I'm just hoping that they are reserving a kiss or sex for the right moment and for a good reason - when they are both ready....
question: I'm just hoping that they are reserving a kiss or sex for the right moment and for a good reason - when they are both ready. Because we all know they want to, and it's been two seasons, but why haven't they yet? Just hoping it's bc they want it to be at the right, good moment...
answer:
I think it’s inevitable that they will cross that line at some point. I don’t know when that will happen, but I do know that, given the circumstances, season 2 wasn’t the right time. On the one hand, we have Eve who has a lot of anger inside her, she’s being kind of rude to Villanelle for the most part of their face to face interactions. She cares about Villanelle but she’s still in denial. On the other hand, we have Villanelle who has fully embraced her feelings for Eve and she’ll do anything to get her. Eve is getting darker gradually but slowly, while Villanelle wants to speed up that process. Which is why Villanelle makes the decision to push Eve into killing Raymond, even though it would be so easy for her to pick up her gun and do it herself. What Villanelle doesn’t realize is that she should have never made that decision for Eve. They both need to learn to respect each other’s autonomy, because they both like to be in control and they both try to control each other. So, they need to find a balance there.

Imagine if a kiss was squeezed in before Eve realizes that Villanelle made her kill someone and Villanelle shoots her. It would feel out of place and it would be ugly. Or imagine if they run away together and how this would affect and restrict the story in the future. Villanelle’s plan to go to Alaska, live together in a cabin where nobody could find them, have a normal life where Villanelle looks after Eve and cooks dinner for her. That’s just naïve. Villanelle wants that normalcy with Eve, but what made her connect with Eve is that she felt that she got accepted for being herself for the first time in her life. And Eve had that normal life before and she was bored of it. It just wouldn’t work for so many reasons. It’s been two seasons as you said, anon. Only two seasons! This show can go on for 2-3 more seasons. The moment will come naturally, when the characters have grown enough
